<br>
Illistyl was a hunter, and for two centuries, her existence had been as pure and empty as any predators. She fed when she was hungry, grew fat when food was plentiful and lean when times were hard. She held her territory against trespassers, but retreated from fights where she might be killed. And in this long and empty time she knew peace from the worries of her long existence. There were many months where she went without the burden of a single thought.<br>
<br>
But she could feel the seasons changing, and the beast within her knew it to be more than the turning of the year. She smelled the wind and was uneasy. She gazed up at the stars with her elven eyes and saw disorder. She slept restlessly, and her dreams were not visions of hunter and prey, but memories of the time before this time.<br>
<br>
Yet, her heart rejected the urges of her instincts, and she curled deeper into her empty dream if a simple, animal life. Let the stars fall into disorder; let the wind blow rich with strife. What could a beast do In the face of fate? Illistyl went on with her simple fantasy, heedless of more complicated urges. And then, one morning, she gazed into a half-frozen, burbling brook and told her reflection what she felt in her heart and knew to be true, “He has gone away.” The trees of the snow-covered forest rustled overhead, scoring her words. “You’ll not see him again.” Her eyes beheld the sun’s light off the crystalline ice, and she felt a grief that she had never known for more than two-hundred years.<br>
<br>
Illistyl dropped to the ground in silence, her silver armor glittering in the dawn sun. She was on her knees in the golden light and shadows and stared at her reflection in the water. “My dear, sweet ranger, I forgot tell you....that I love you.” Her own crystal blue eyes stared back at her as she ripped the tiara from its tangled nest of golden hair, seeing for the first time in decades a tear-streaked face. Bracing her hands in the frozen stream-bank, she sobbed, and burning tears mixed with the icy water below.<br>
